# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: eukaryotic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] An **adjective** (abbreviated **ADJ**) is a word that describes or defines a noun or noun phrase.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] The adjective is considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including *the*, *this*, *my*, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Depending on the language, an adjective can precede a corresponding noun on a prepositive basis or it can follow a corresponding noun on a postpositive basis.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Structural, contextual, and style considerations can impinge on the pre-or post-position of an adjective in a given instance of its occurrence.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Adjectives feature as a part of speech (word class) in most languages.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In some languages, the words that serve the semantic function of adjectives are categorized together with some other class, such as nouns or verbs.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In the phrase *a Ford car*, *Ford* is unquestionably a noun but its function is adjectival (noun adjunct, see below): to modify *car*.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In some languages adjectives can function as nouns: for example, the Spanish phrase *un rojo* means 'a red [one]'.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] This is also possible in English, see above.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] As for "confusion" with verbs, rather than an adjective meaning "big", a language might have a verb that means "to be big" and could then use an attributive verb construction analogous to "big-being house" to express what in English is called a "big house".
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Such an analysis is possible for the grammar of Standard Chinese and Korean, for example.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Different languages do not use adjectives in exactly the same situations.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] For example, where English uses *"*to be *hungry*" (*hungry* being an adjective), Dutch, French, and Spanish use "*honger hebben*", "*avoir faim*", and "*tener hambre*" respectively (literally "to have hunger", the words for "hunger" being nouns).
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Similarly, where Hebrew uses the adjective זקוק‎ (*zaqūq*, roughly "in need of" or "needing"), English uses the verb "to need".
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In languages that have adjectives as a word class, it is usually an open class; that is, it is relatively common for new adjectives to be formed via such processes as derivation.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] However, Bantu languages are well known for having only a small closed class of adjectives, and new adjectives are not easily derived.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Similarly, native Japanese adjectives (*i*-adjectives) are considered a closed class (as are native verbs), although nouns (an open class) may be used in the genitive to convey some adjectival meanings, and there is also the separate open class of adjectival nouns (*na*-adjectives).
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Many languages (including English) distinguish between adjectives, which qualify nouns and pronouns, and adverbs, which mainly modify verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Not all languages make this exact distinction; many (including English) have words that can function as either.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] For example, in English, *fast* is an adjective in "a *fast* car" (where it qualifies the noun *car*) but an adverb in "he drove *fast*" (where it modifies the verb *drove*).
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] A German word like *klug* ("clever(ly)") takes endings when used as an attributive adjective but not when used adverbially.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Whether these are distinct parts of speech or distinct usages of the same part of speech is a question of analysis.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] While German linguistic terminology distinguishes *adverbiale* from *adjektivische Formen*, German refers to both as *Eigenschaftswörter* ("property words").
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Linguists today distinguish determiners from adjectives, considering them to be two separate parts of speech (or *lexical categories*).
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Determiners formerly were considered to be adjectives in some of their uses.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Determiners function neither as nouns nor pronouns but instead characterize a nominal element within a particular context.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] They generally do this by indicating definiteness (*a* vs.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] An adjective acts as the head of an *adjective phrase* or *adjectival phrase* (AP).
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In the simplest case, an adjective phrase consists solely of the adjective; more complex adjective phrases may contain one or more adverbs modifying the adjective ("*very* strong"), or one or more complements (such as "worth *several dollars*", "full *of toys*", or "eager *to please*").
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In English, attributive adjective phrases that include complements typically follow the noun that they qualify ("an evildoer *devoid of redeeming qualities*").
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In many languages (including English) it is possible for nouns to modify other nouns.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Unlike adjectives, nouns acting as modifiers (called *attributive nouns* or *noun adjuncts*) usually are not predicative; a beautiful park is beautiful, but a car park is not "car".
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] The modifier often indicates origin ("*Virginia* reel"), purpose ("*work* clothes"), semantic patient ("*man* eater") or semantic subject ("*child* actor"); however, it may generally indicate almost any semantic relationship.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] It is also common for adjectives to be derived from nouns, as in *boyish*, *birdlike*, *behavioral (behavioural)*, *famous*, *manly*, *angelic*, and so on.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Many languages have participle forms that can act as noun modifiers either alone or as the head of a phrase.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Sometimes participles develop into functional usage as adjectives.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Examples in English include *relieved* (the past participle of *relieve*), used as an adjective in passive voice constructs such as "I am so *relieved* to see you".
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Other examples include *spoken* (the past participle of *speak*) and *going* (the present participle of *go*), which function as attribute adjectives in such phrases as "the *spoken* word" and "the *going* rate".
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Other constructs that often modify nouns include prepositional phrases (as in "a rebel *without a cause*"), relative clauses (as in "the man *who wasn't there*"), and infinitive phrases (as in "a cake *to die for*").
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Some nouns can also take complements such as content clauses (as in "the idea *that I would do that*"), but these are not commonly considered modifiers.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] For more information about possible modifiers and dependents of nouns, see Components of noun phrases.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In Australian Aboriginal languages, the distinction between adjectives and nouns is typically thought weak, and many of the languages only use nouns, or nouns with a limited set of adjective-deriving affixes, to modify other nouns.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In languages that have a subtle adjective-noun distinction, one way to tell them apart is that a modifying adjective can come to stand in for an entire elided noun phrase, while a modifying noun cannot.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] For example, in Bardi, the adjective *moorrooloo* 'little' in the phrase *moorrooloo* *baawa* 'little child' can stand on its own to mean 'the little one', while the attributive noun *aamba* 'man' in the phrase *aamba baawa* 'male child' cannot stand for the whole phrase to mean 'the male one'.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In other languages, like Warlpiri, nouns and adjectives are lumped together beneath the nominal umbrella because of their shared syntactic distribution as arguments of predicates.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] The only thing distinguishing them is that some nominals seem to semantically denote entities (typically nouns in English) and some nominals seem to denote attributes (typically adjectives in English).
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In many languages, attributive adjectives usually occur in a specific order.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In general, the adjective order in English can be summarised as: opinion, size, age or shape, colour, origin, material, purpose.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Other language authorities, like the *Cambridge Dictionary*, state that shape precedes rather than follows age.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Determiners and postdeterminers—articles, numerals, and other limiters (e.g.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] *three* blind mice)—come before attributive adjectives in English.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Although certain combinations of determiners can appear before a noun, they are far more circumscribed than adjectives in their use—typically, only a single determiner would appear before a noun or noun phrase (including any attributive adjectives).
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Size – adjectives denoting physical size (e.g.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Shape or physical quality – adjectives describing more detailed physical attributes than overall size (e.g.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Colour – adjectives denoting colour or pattern (e.g.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Origin – denominal adjectives denoting source (e.g.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] This means that, in English, adjectives pertaining to size precede adjectives pertaining to age ("little old", not "old little"), which in turn generally precede adjectives pertaining to colour ("old white", not "white old").
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] This order may be more rigid in some languages than others; in some, like Spanish, it may only be a default (*unmarked*) word order, with other orders being permissible.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Other languages, such as Tagalog, follow their adjectival orders as rigidly as English.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] The normal adjectival order of English may be overridden in certain circumstances, especially when one adjective is being fronted or with ablaut reduplication.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] For example, the usual order of adjectives in English would result in the phrase "the bad big wolf" (opinion before size), but instead, the usual phrase is "the big bad wolf".
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Owing partially to borrowings from French, English has some adjectives that follow the noun as postmodifiers, called postpositive adjectives, as in *time immemorial* and *attorney general*.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Adjectives may even change meaning depending on whether they precede or follow, as in *proper*: "They live in a *proper town*" (a real town, not a village) vs.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] "They live in the *town proper* (in the town itself, not in the suburbs).
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In many languages, some adjectives are *comparable* and the measure of comparison is called *degree*.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] For example, a person may be "polite", but another person may be "*more* polite", and a third person may be the "*most* polite" of the three.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] The word "more" here modifies the adjective "polite" to indicate a comparison is being made, and "most" modifies the adjective to indicate an absolute comparison (a *superlative*).
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Among languages that allow adjectives to be compared, different means are used to indicate comparison.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Some languages do not distinguish between comparative and superlative forms.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Other languages allow adjectives to be compared but do not have a special comparative form of the adjective.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In such cases, as in some Australian Aboriginal languages, case-marking, such as the ablative case, may be used to indicate one entity has more of an adjectival quality than (i.e.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Another way to convey comparison is by incorporating the words "more" and "most".
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] There is no simple rule to decide which means is correct for any given adjective, however.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] The general tendency is for simpler adjectives and those from Anglo-Saxon to take the suffixes, while longer adjectives and those from French, Latin, or Greek do not—but sometimes the *sound* of the word is the deciding factor.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Many adjectives do not naturally lend themselves to comparison.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] For example, some English speakers would argue that it does not make sense to say that one thing is "more ultimate" than another, or that something is "most ultimate", since the word "ultimate" is already absolute in its semantics.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Such adjectives are called *non-comparable* or *absolute*.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Nevertheless, native speakers will frequently play with the raised forms of adjectives of this sort.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Although "pregnant" is logically non-comparable (either one is pregnant or not), one may hear a sentence like "She looks more and more pregnant each day".
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Comparative and superlative forms are also occasionally used for other purposes than comparison.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In Italian, superlatives are frequently used to put strong emphasis on an adjective: *bellissimo* means "most beautiful", but is in fact more commonly heard in the sense "extremely beautiful".
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Attributive adjectives and other noun modifiers may be used either *restrictively* (helping to identify the noun's referent, hence "restricting" its reference) or *non-restrictively* (helping to describe a noun).
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Here "difficult" is restrictive – it tells which tasks he avoids, distinguishing these from the easy ones: "Only those tasks that are difficult".
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In English, restrictiveness is not marked on adjectives but is marked on relative clauses (the difference between "the man *who recognized me* was there" and "the man, *who recognized me*, was there" being one of restrictiveness).
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In some languages, adjectives alter their form to reflect the gender, case and number of the noun that they describe.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Here, a distinction may be made between attributive and predicative usage.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] In English, adjectives never agree, whereas in French, they always agree.
[src:eukaryotic/adjective] Semanticist Barbara Partee classifies adjectives semantically as intersective, subsective, or nonsubsective, with nonsubsective adjectives being plain nonsubsective or privative.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The **eukaryotes** (/juːˈkærioʊts, -əts/) are the domain **Eukaryota** or **Eukarya**, organisms whose cells have a membrane-bound nucleus.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] All animals, plants, fungi, seaweeds, and many unicellular organisms are eukaryotes.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] They constitute a major group of life forms alongside the two groups of prokaryotes: the Bacteria and the Archaea.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Eukaryotes represent a small minority of the number of organisms, but given their generally much larger size, their collective global biomass is much larger than that of prokaryotes.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The eukaryotes emerged within the archaeal phylum Promethearchaeota.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Ignoring mitochondrial DNA (which is bacterial rather than archaeal), this would imply only two domains of life, Bacteria and Archaea, with eukaryotes incorporated among the Archaea.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Eukaryotes first emerged during the Paleoproterozoic, likely as flagellated cells.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The leading evolutionary theory is they were created by symbiogenesis between an anaerobic Promethearchaeota archaeon and an aerobic proteobacterium, which formed the mitochondria.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] A second episode of symbiogenesis with a cyanobacterium created the plants, with chloroplasts.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Eukaryotic cells contain membrane-bound organelles such as the nucleus, the endoplasmic reticulum, and the Golgi apparatus.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Eukaryotes may be either unicellular or multicellular.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] In comparison, prokaryotes are typically unicellular.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Unicellular eukaryotes are sometimes called protists.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Eukaryotes can reproduce both asexually through mitosis and sexually through meiosis and gamete fusion (fertilization).
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The word *eukaryote* is derived from the Greek words "eu" (εὖ) meaning "true" or "good" and "karyon" (κάρυον) meaning "nut" or "kernel", referring to the nucleus of a cell.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Eukaryotes are organisms that range from microscopic single cells, such as picozoans under 3 micrometers across, to animals like the blue whale, weighing up to 190 tonnes and measuring up to 33.6 meters (110 ft) long, or plants like the coast redwood, up to 120 meters (390 ft) tall.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Many eukaryotes are unicellular; the informal grouping called protists includes many of these, with some multicellular forms like the giant kelp up to 200 feet (61 m) long.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The multicellular eukaryotes include the animals, plants, and fungi, but again, these groups too contain many unicellular species.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Eukaryotic cells are typically much larger than those of prokaryotes—the bacteria and the archaea—having a volume of around 10,000 times greater.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Eukaryotes represent a small minority of the number of organisms, but, as many of them are much larger, their collective global biomass (468 gigatons) is far larger than that of prokaryotes (77 gigatons), with plants alone accounting for over 81% of the total biomass of Earth.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The eukaryotes are a diverse lineage, consisting mainly of microscopic organisms.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Multicellularity in some form has evolved independently at least 25 times within the eukaryotes.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Complex multicellular organisms, not counting the aggregation of amoebae to form slime molds, have evolved within only six eukaryotic lineages: animals, symbiomycotan fungi, brown algae, red algae, green algae, and land plants.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Eukaryotes are grouped by genomic similarities, so that groups often lack visible shared characteristics.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The defining feature of eukaryotes is that their cells have a well-defined, membrane-bound nucleus, distinguishing them from prokaryotes that lack such a structure.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Eukaryotic cells have a variety of internal membrane-bound structures, called organelles, and a cytoskeleton which defines the cell's organization and shape.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The nucleus stores the cell's DNA, which is divided into linear bundles called chromosomes; these are separated into two matching sets by a microtubular spindle during nuclear division, in the distinctively eukaryotic process of mitosis.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Eukaryotes differ from prokaryotes in multiple ways, with unique biochemical pathways such as sterane synthesis.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The eukaryotic signature proteins have no homology to proteins in other domains of life, but appear to be universal among eukaryotes.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] They include the proteins of the cytoskeleton, the complex transcription machinery, the membrane-sorting systems, the nuclear pore, and some enzymes in the biochemical pathways.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Eukaryote cells include a variety of membrane-bound structures, together forming the endomembrane system.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Simple compartments, called vesicles and vacuoles, can form by budding off other membranes.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Many cells ingest food and other materials through a process of endocytosis, where the outer membrane invaginates and then pinches off to form a vesicle.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Some cell products can leave in a vesicle through exocytosis.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The nucleus is surrounded by a double membrane known as the nuclear envelope, with nuclear pores that allow material to move in and out.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Various tube- and sheet-like extensions of the nuclear membrane form the endoplasmic reticulum, which is involved in protein transport and maturation.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] It includes the rough endoplasmic reticulum, covered in ribosomes which synthesize proteins; these enter the interior space or lumen.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Subsequently, they generally enter vesicles, which bud off from the smooth endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] In most eukaryotes, these protein-carrying vesicles are released and their contents further modified in stacks of flattened vesicles (cisternae), the Golgi apparatus.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Vesicles may be specialized; for instance, lysosomes contain digestive enzymes that break down biomolecules in the cytoplasm.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Mitochondria are organelles in eukaryotic cells.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The mitochondrion is commonly called "the powerhouse of the cell", for its function providing energy by oxidizing sugars or fats to produce the energy-storing molecule ATP.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Mitochondria have two surrounding membranes, each a phospholipid bilayer, the inner of which is folded into invaginations called cristae where aerobic respiration takes place.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Mitochondria contain their own DNA, which has close structural similarities to bacterial DNA, from which it originated, and which encodes rRNA and tRNA genes that produce RNA which is closer in structure to bacterial RNA than to eukaryote RNA.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Some eukaryotes, such as the metamonads *Giardia* and *Trichomonas*, and the amoebozoan *Pelomyxa*, appear to lack mitochondria, but all contain mitochondrion-derived organelles, like hydrogenosomes or mitosomes, having lost their mitochondria secondarily.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] They obtain energy by enzymatic action in the cytoplasm.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] It is thought that mitochondria developed from prokaryotic cells which became endosymbionts living inside eukaryotes.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Plants and various groups of algae have plastids as well as mitochondria.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Plastids, like mitochondria, have their own DNA and are developed from endosymbionts, in this case cyanobacteria.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] They usually take the form of chloroplasts which, like cyanobacteria, contain chlorophyll and produce organic compounds (such as glucose) through photosynthesis.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Although plastids probably had a single origin, not all plastid-containing groups are closely related.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Instead, some eukaryotes have obtained them from other eukaryotes through secondary endosymbiosis or ingestion.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The capture and sequestering of photosynthetic cells and chloroplasts, kleptoplasty, occurs in many types of modern eukaryotic organisms.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The cytoskeleton provides stiffening structure and points of attachment for motor structures that enable the cell to move, change shape, or transport materials.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The motor structures are microfilaments of actin and actin-binding proteins.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] These include α-actinin, fimbrin, and filamin in submembranous cortical layers and bundles.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Motor proteins of microtubules, dynein and kinesin, and myosin of actin filaments, make the network dynamic.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Many eukaryotes have long slender motile cytoplasmic projections, called flagella, or multiple shorter structures called cilia.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] These organelles are variously involved in movement, feeding, and sensation.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] They are composed mainly of tubulin, and are entirely distinct from prokaryotic flagella.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] They are supported by a bundle of microtubules arising from a centriole, characteristically arranged as nine doublets surrounding two singlets.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Flagella may have hairs (mastigonemes), as in many stramenopiles.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Their interior is continuous with the cell's cytoplasm.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Centrioles are often present, even in cells and groups that do not have flagella, but conifers and flowering plants have neither.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] They generally occur in groups that give rise to various microtubular roots.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] These form a primary component of the cytoskeleton, and are often assembled over the course of several cell divisions, with one flagellum retained from the parent and the other derived from it.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Centrioles produce the spindle during nuclear division.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The cells of plants, algae, fungi and most chromalveolates, but not animals, are surrounded by a cell wall.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] This is a layer outside the cell membrane, providing the cell with structural support, protection, and a filtering mechanism.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The cell wall also prevents over-expansion when water enters the cell.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The major polysaccharides making up the primary cell wall of land plants are cellulose, hemicellulose, and pectin.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The cellulose microfibrils are linked together with hemicellulose, embedded in a pectin matrix.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The most common hemicellulose in the primary cell wall is xyloglucan.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Eukaryotes have a life cycle that involves sexual reproduction, alternating between a haploid phase, where only one copy of each chromosome is present in each cell, and a diploid phase, with two copies of each chromosome in each cell.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] There is considerable variation in this pattern.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Plants have both haploid and diploid multicellular phases.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Eukaryotes have lower metabolic rates and longer generation times than prokaryotes, because they are larger and therefore have a smaller surface area to volume ratio.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The evolution of sexual reproduction may be a primordial characteristic of eukaryotes.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Based on a phylogenetic analysis, Dacks and Roger have proposed that facultative sex was present in the group's common ancestor.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] A core set of genes that function in meiosis is present in both *Trichomonas vaginalis* and *Giardia intestinalis*, two organisms previously thought to be asexual.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Since these two species are descendants of lineages that diverged early from the eukaryotic evolutionary tree, core meiotic genes, and hence sex, were likely present in the common ancestor of eukaryotes.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Species once thought to be asexual, such as *Leishmania* parasites, have a sexual cycle.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Amoebae, previously regarded as asexual, may be anciently sexual; while present-day asexual groups could have arisen recently.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] In antiquity, the two lineages of animals and plants were recognized by Aristotle and Theophrastus.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The lineages were given the taxonomic rank of kingdom by Linnaeus in the 18th century.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Though he included the fungi with plants with some reservations, it was later realized that they are quite distinct and warrant a separate kingdom.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The various single-cell eukaryotes were originally placed with plants or animals when they became known.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Goldfuss coined the word *Protozoa* to refer to organisms such as ciliates, and this group was expanded until Ernst Haeckel made it a kingdom encompassing all single-celled eukaryotes, the Protista, in 1866.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The protists were at that time thought to be "primitive forms", and thus an evolutionary grade, united by their primitive unicellular nature.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] In 1996, the evolutionary biologist Lynn Margulis proposed to replace kingdoms and domains with "inclusive" names to create a "symbiosis-based phylogeny", giving the description "Eukarya (symbiosis-derived nucleated organisms)".
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] By the early 21st century, a rough consensus started to emerge from phylogenomic studies.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The majority of eukaryotes can be placed in one of two large clades dubbed Amorphea (similar in composition to the unikont hypothesis) and the Diphoda (formerly bikonts), which includes plants and most algal lineages.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] A third major grouping, the Excavata, has been abandoned as a formal group as it was found to be paraphyletic.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The proposed phylogeny below includes two groups of excavates (Discoba and Metamonada), and incorporates the 2021 proposal that picozoans are close relatives of rhodophytes.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The Provora are a group of microbial predators discovered in 2022.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] TSAR is a possible clade that would contain Telonemia and the SAR supergroup.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] One view of the great kingdoms and their stem groups.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The Metamonada are hard to place, being sister possibly to Discoba or to Malawimonadida or being a paraphyletic group external to all other eukaryotes.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Eukaryotes are thought to have emerged within the archaeal phylum Promethearchaeota.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The origin of the eukaryotic cell, or *eukaryogenesis*, is a milestone in the evolution of life, since eukaryotes include all complex cells and almost all multicellular organisms.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The last eukaryotic common ancestor (LECA) is the hypothetical origin of all living eukaryotes, and was most likely a biological population, not a single individual.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The LECA is believed to have been a protist with a nucleus, at least one centriole and flagellum, facultatively aerobic mitochondria, sex (meiosis and syngamy), a dormant cyst with a cell wall of chitin or cellulose, and peroxisomes.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] An endosymbiotic union between a motile anaerobic archaean and an aerobic alphaproteobacterium gave rise to the LECA and all eukaryotes with mitochondria.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] A second, much later endosymbiosis with a cyanobacterium gave rise to the ancestor of plants, with chloroplasts.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The presence of eukaryotic biomarkers in archaea points towards an archaeal origin, except for mitochondrial DNA, which is bacterial in origin.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The genomes of Promethearchaeota archaea have plenty of eukaryotic signature protein genes, which play a crucial role in the development of the cytoskeleton and complex cellular structures characteristic of eukaryotes.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] In 2022, cryo-electron tomography demonstrated that Promethearchaeota archaea have a complex actin-based cytoskeleton, providing the first direct visual evidence of the archaeal ancestry of eukaryotes.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The timing of the origin of eukaryotes is hard to determine.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Multiple different fossils that may be early eukaryotes have been suggested, but remain contested.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Fossils that are clearly related to modern groups start appearing an estimated 1.2 billion years ago, in the form of red algae, though fossilized Vindhyan filamentous algae have been suggested to be as much as 1.6 to 1.7 billion years old, rather than Cambrian as previously thought.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] A 2026 study suggests that early fossil eukaryotes (1.75-1.4 Gya) may have been benthic aerobes, living on the bottom of oxygenated waters, and may not have colonised planktonic environments until much later, after 1 Gya.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Fossils from the Ruyang Group of China, dating to approximately 1.8-1.6 billion years ago, may be the oldest known eukaryotes.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] One possible earliest multicellular eukaryote fossil is *Qingshania magnifica* from North China, which lived 1.635 billion years ago.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] This would suggest that the crown group eukaryotes originated in the late Paleoproterozoic (Statherian).
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Other early unicellular eukaryotes, *Tappania plana*, *Shuiyousphaeridium macroreticulatum*, *Dictyosphaera macroreticulata*, *Germinosphaera alveolata*, and *Valeria lophostriata* from North China, lived approximately 1.65 billion years ago.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Some acritarchs are known from at least 1.65 billion years ago, and a fossil, *Grypania*, which may be an alga, is as much as 2.1 billion years old.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The "problematic" fossil *Diskagma* has been found in paleosols 2.2 billion years old.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The Neoarchean fossil *Thuchomyces* shares some similarities with fungi.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] It especially resembles the problematic fossil *Diskagma*, with hyphae and multiple differentiated layers.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] However, it is over 600 million years older than all other possible eukaryotes, and many of its "eukaryote features" are not specific to the clade, meaning it is almost certainly a microbial mat instead.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] Structures proposed to represent "large colonial organisms" have been found in the black shales of the Palaeoproterozoic such as the Francevillian B Formation, in Gabon, dubbed the "Francevillian biota" which is dated at 2.1 billion years old.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] However, the status of these structures as fossils is contested, with other authors suggesting that they might represent pseudofossils.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The presence of steranes, eukaryotic-specific biomarkers, in Australian shales previously indicated that eukaryotes were present in these rocks dated at 2.7 billion years old, but these Archaean biomarkers have been rebutted as later contaminants.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The oldest valid biomarker records are only around 800 million years old.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] In contrast, a molecular clock analysis suggests the emergence of sterol biosynthesis as early as 2.3 billion years ago.
[src:eukaryotic/eukaryote] The nature of steranes as eukaryotic biomarkers is further complicated by the production of sterols by some bacteria.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] In grammar, a **noun** is a word that represents a concrete or abstract thing, like living creatures, places, actions, events, qualities, states of existence, and ideas.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] To summarize this, nouns signify an object or idea.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] A noun may serve as an object or subject within a phrase, clause, or sentence.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] In linguistics, nouns constitute a lexical category (part of speech) defined according to how its members combine with members of other lexical categories.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] The syntactic occurrence of nouns differs among languages.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] In English, prototypical nouns are common nouns or proper nouns that can occur with determiners, articles and attributive adjectives, and can function as the head of a noun phrase.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] According to traditional and popular classification, pronouns are distinct from nouns, but in much modern theory they are considered a subclass of nouns.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Every language has various linguistic and grammatical distinctions between nouns and verbs.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Word classes (parts of speech) were described by Sanskrit grammarians from at least the 5th century BC.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] In Yāska's *Nirukta*, the noun (*nāma*) is one of the four main categories of words defined.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] The Ancient Greek equivalent was *ónoma* (ὄνομα), referred to by Plato in the *Cratylus*, and later listed as one of the eight parts of speech in *The Art of Grammar*, attributed to Dionysius Thrax (2nd century BC).
[src:eukaryotic/noun] The term used in Latin grammar was *nōmen*.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] All of these terms for "noun" were also words meaning "name".
[src:eukaryotic/noun] The English word *noun* is derived from the Latin term, through the Anglo-Norman *nom* (other forms include *nomme*, and *noun* itself).
[src:eukaryotic/noun] The word classes were defined partly by the grammatical forms that they take.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] In Sanskrit, Greek, and Latin, for example, nouns are categorized by gender and inflected for case and number.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Because adjectives share these three grammatical categories, adjectives typically were placed in the same class as nouns.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Similarly, the Latin term *nōmen* includes both nouns (substantives) and adjectives, as originally did the English word *noun*, the two types being distinguished as *nouns substantive* and *nouns adjective* (or *substantive nouns* and *adjective nouns*, or simply *substantives* and *adjectives*).
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Many European languages use a cognate of the word *substantive* as the basic term for *noun* (for example, Spanish *sustantivo*, "noun").
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Nouns in the dictionaries of such languages are demarked by the abbreviation *s.* or *sb.* instead of *n.*, which may be used for proper nouns or neuter nouns instead.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] In English, some modern authors use the word *substantive* to refer to a class that includes both nouns (single words) and noun phrases (multiword units that are sometimes called *noun equivalents*).
[src:eukaryotic/noun] It can also be used as a counterpart to *attributive* when distinguishing between a noun being used as the head (main word) of a noun phrase and a noun being used as a noun adjunct.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] For example, the noun *knee* can be said to be used substantively in *my knee hurts*, but attributively in *the patient needed knee replacement*.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] A noun can co-occur with an article or an attributive adjective.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] In the following, an asterisk (*) in front of an example means that this example is ungrammatical.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Nouns have sometimes been characterized in terms of the grammatical categories by which they may be varied (for example gender, case, and number).
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Such definitions tend to be language-specific, since different languages may apply different categories.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Nouns are frequently defined, particularly in informal contexts, in terms of their semantic properties (their meanings).
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Nouns are described as words that refer to a *person*, *place*, *thing*, *event*, *substance*, *quality*, *quantity*, etc., but this manner of definition has been criticized as uninformative.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Several English nouns lack an intrinsic referent of their own: *behalf* (as in *on behalf of*), *dint* (*by dint of*), and *sake* (*for the sake of*).
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Moreover, other parts of speech may have reference-like properties: the verbs *to rain* or *to mother*, or adjectives like *red*; and there is little difference between the adverb *gleefully* and the prepositional phrase *with glee*.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] A functional approach defines a noun as a word that can be the head of a nominal phrase, i.e., a phrase with referential function, without needing to go through morphological transformation.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Nouns can have a number of different properties and are often sub-categorized based on various of these criteria, depending on their occurrence in a language.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Nouns may be classified according to morphological properties such as which prefixes or suffixes they take, and also their relations in syntax – how they combine with other words and expressions of various types.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Many such classifications are language-specific, given the obvious differences in syntax and morphology.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] In English for example, it might be noted that nouns are words that can co-occur with definite articles (as stated at the start of this article), but this could not apply in Russian, which has no definite articles.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] In some languages common and proper nouns have grammatical gender, typically masculine, feminine, and neuter.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] The gender of a noun (as well as its number and case, where applicable) will often require agreement in words that modify or are used along with it.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] In French for example, the singular form of the definite article is *le* for masculine nouns and *la* for feminine; adjectives and certain verb forms also change (sometimes with the simple addition of *-e* for feminine).
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Grammatical gender often correlates with the form of the noun and the inflection pattern it follows; for example, in both Italian and Romanian most nouns ending in *-a* are feminine.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Gender can also correlate with the sex or social gender of the noun's referent, particularly in the case of nouns denoting people (and sometimes animals), though with exceptions (the feminine French noun *personne* can refer to a male or a female person).
[src:eukaryotic/noun] In Modern English, even common nouns like *hen* and *princess* and proper nouns like *Alicia* do not have grammatical gender (their femininity has no relevance in syntax), though they denote persons or animals of a specific sex.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] The gender of a pronoun must be appropriate for the item referred to: "The *girl* said the *ring* was from *her* new *boyfriend*, but *he* denied *it* was from *him*" (three nouns; and three gendered pronouns: or four, if this *her* is counted as a possessive pronoun).
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Many nouns have both countable and uncountable uses; for example, *soda* is countable in "give me three sodas", but uncountable in "he likes soda".
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Some nouns have both concrete and abstract meanings: *art* usually refers to something abstract ("Art is important in human culture"), but it can also refer to a concrete item ("I put my daughter's art up on the fridge").
[src:eukaryotic/noun] A noun might have a literal (concrete) and also a figurative (abstract) meaning: "a brass *key*" and "the *key* to success"; "a *block* in the pipe" and "a mental *block*".
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Similarly, some abstract nouns have developed etymologically by figurative extension from literal roots (*drawback*, *fraction*, *holdout*, *uptake*).
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Many abstract nouns in English are formed by adding a suffix (*-ness*, *-ity*, *-ion*) to adjectives or verbs (*happiness* and *serenity* from the adjectives *happy* and *serene*; *circulation* from the verb *circulate*).
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Illustrating the wide range of possible classifying principles for nouns, the Awa language of Papua New Guinea regiments nouns according to how *ownership* is assigned: as alienable possession or inalienable possession.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] An alienably possessed item (a tree, for example) can exist even without a possessor.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] But inalienably possessed items are necessarily associated with their possessor and are referred to differently, for example with nouns that function as kin terms (meaning "father", etc.), body-part nouns (meaning "shadow", "hair", etc.), or part–whole nouns (meaning "top", "bottom", etc.).
[src:eukaryotic/noun] A noun phrase (or **NP**) is a phrase usually headed by a common noun, a proper noun, or a pronoun.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] The head may be the only constituent, or it may be modified by determiners and adjectives.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] For example, "The dog sat near Ms Curtis and wagged its tail" contains three NPs: *the dog* (subject of the verbs *sat* and *wagged*); *Ms Curtis* (complement of the preposition *near*); and *its tail* (object of *wagged*).
[src:eukaryotic/noun] "You became their teacher" contains two NPs: *you* (subject of *became*); and *their teacher*.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] For example, in the sentence "Gareth thought she was weird", the word *she* is a pronoun that refers to a person just as the noun *Gareth* does.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] The word *one* can replace parts of noun phrases, and it sometimes stands in for a noun.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] But *one* can also stand in for larger parts of a noun phrase.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] For example, in the following example, *one* can stand in for *new car*.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] Nominalization is a process whereby a word that belongs to another part of speech comes to be used as a noun.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] This can be a way to create new nouns, or to use other words in ways that resemble nouns.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] In French and Spanish, for example, adjectives frequently act as nouns referring to people who have the characteristics denoted by the adjective.
[src:eukaryotic/noun] is a worldwide association of political parties.
